,'1441711587'),(813,93,'_wp_trash_meta_status','publish'),(814,93,'_wp_trash_meta_time','1441711587'),(815,1,'_wp_trash_meta_status','publish'),(816,1,'_wp_trash_meta_time','1441711594'),(817,1,'_wp_trash_meta_comments_status','a:1:{i:1;s:1:\"1\";}'),(838,28,'panels_data','a:3:{s:7:\"widgets\";a:2:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"title\";s:0:\"\";s:4:\"text\";s:37840:\"<div id=\"inner\"><div class=\"wrap\"><div id=\"content-sidebar-wrap\"><div id=\"content\" class=\"hfeed\"><div class=\"post-1316 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-eye-care category-eye-examination category-eye-facts category-eye-health category-news entry\"><h2 class=\"entry-title\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/10-signs-that-you-need-to-book-an-eye-exam/\" rel=\"bookmark\">10 signs that you need to book an eye exam</a></h2> \n<div class=\"post-info\"><span class=\"date published time\" title=\"2015-06-07T18:00:53+00:00\">07/06/2015</span>  by <span class=\"author vcard\"><span class=\"fn\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/author/admin/\" rel=\"author\">admin</a></span></span> ·  </div><div class=\"entry-content\"><p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-1318\" src=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/Screen-Shot-2015-06-07-at-5.54.24-pm.png\" alt=\"Screen Shot 2015-06-07 at 5.54.24 pm\" width=\"950\" height=\"321\"></p>\n<p>Here at Campuspecs, your <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/our-location/\">Auckland CBD optometrist</a>, we recommend you have regular eye exams; after all you only have one pair of eyes so keeping them healthy is really important. Not only that but a simple eye test can do more than assess your sight; warning signs for a range of life threatening illnesses can be detected in the inner workings of the eye.</p>\n<p>So how regular is regular? Well as a general rule of thumb we recommend adults have eye exams approximately every two years, but your personal requirement can also depend on a few varying factors…</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Your age</li>\n<li>Whether you currently wear corrective lenses</li>\n<li>Whether you have a family history of glaucoma or macular degeneration</li>\n<li>Whether you suffer from diabetes, an existing eye disorder; or have had eye surgery or suffered a trauma to the eye.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Nevertheless, there are often signs and symptoms associated with a more urgent requirement to visit your optometrist. So here are a few signs that should serve as a reminder to make an immediate appointment for your next eye examination.</p>\n<ol>\n<li>You can’t remember the last time you visited an optometrist</li>\n<li>You have begun suffering from blurred vision or are having problems focusing</li>\n<li>You are seeing spots, flashes of light, or floaters</li>\n<li>Your eyes are dry, red or itchy</li>\n<li>You’re getting frequent headaches</li>\n<li>Your eyes are not adjusting to different levels of light, and you’re finding it difficult to see in the dark; or your eyes are sensitive to light</li>\n<li>You’re squinting</li>\n<li>You’re suffering from motion sickness or dizziness</li>\n<li>You feel you need longer arms! i.e. You’re holding reading material further and further away from you</li>\n<li>You’re suffering from or have recently suffered from an eye infection</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Don’t forget if you’re an Auckland local, who hasn’t yet taken up the Campuspecs offer of a FREE, comprehensive eye examination. We have extended this offer until the end of June! Your complimentary eye exam will include retinal photo, visual field screening &amp; intra-ocular pressure check.</p>\n<p><strong><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/appointment-enquiry/\">BOOK HERE</a></strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</div><div class=\"post-meta\"><span class=\"categories\">Filed Under: <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-care/\" rel=\"category tag\">EYE CARE</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-examination/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eye Examination</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-facts/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eye Facts</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-health/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eye Health</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/news/\" rel=\"category tag\">News</a></span> · </div></div><div class=\"post-1309 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-current-offers category-eye-care category-eye-examination category-eye-facts category-eye-health category-news category-workplace-eyecare entry\"><h2 class=\"entry-title\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/your-optometrist-loving-local-auckland-eyes-for-longer/\" rel=\"bookmark\">Your optometrist loving local Auckland eyes for longer…</a></h2> \n<div class=\"post-info\"><span class=\"date published time\" title=\"2015-06-01T12:55:27+00:00\">01/06/2015</span>  by <span class=\"author vcard\"><span class=\"fn\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/author/admin/\" rel=\"author\">admin</a></span></span> ·  </div><div class=\"entry-content\"><p>We have great news for all you Auckland locals, who haven’t yet taken up the Campuspecs offer of a FREE, comprehensive eye examination. We are extending this offer until the end of June!</p>\n<p>Your eye exam will include retinal photo, visual field screening &amp; intra-ocular pressure check.</p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-1289\" src=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/SliderCampus_Offers_1_Apr_May.jpg\" alt=\"SliderCampus_Offers_1_Apr_May\" width=\"960\" height=\"380\"></p>\n<p>You can find out full details <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/eye-exam-deal/\">HERE</a>.</p>\n<p>When you visit Campuspecs for your eye exam, you’ll meet our optometrist Lisa. Lisa is responsible for everything to do with examining your eyes. She performs general eye examinations including checking your prescription (glasses and contacts), eye health and eye pressure. Lisa is a therapeutically qualified optometrist, able to prescribe medicated eye drops for certain eye conditions. She interprets all of the data gathered, and is able to advise on certain eye therapies, and conduct referrals for more serious eye conditions.</p>\n<p><strong>Four reasons why it’s important to have a regular eye exam…</strong></p>\n<ol>\n<li>Many serious eye diseases show no signs or symptoms. A full eye examination can pick up early signs of these eye conditions, including glaucoma, diabetic eye disease or macular degeneration.</li>\n<li>As with many health issues, the earlier a problem with your eyes is detected the more likely it is that it can be successfully treated. Around 80% of all eye conditions are preventable or curable.</li>\n<li>Having your eyes examined regularly, and picking up any problems can help lessen your risk of accidents, be they from, driving, cycling or falling.</li>\n<li>A regular eye exam can increase your productivity. Research cited by the American Optometric Association found that even a minor mis-correction increases the time to complete tasks by 9% and errors by 40%. If you are employer, here at Campuspecs we are able to tailor a <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/workplace-eyecare/\">workplace eye care package</a> to suit your needs and your budget. If you’re an employee tell your boss about it!</li>\n</ol>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</div><div class=\"post-meta\"><span class=\"categories\">Filed Under: <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/current-offers/\" rel=\"category tag\">CURRENT OFFERS</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-care/\" rel=\"category tag\">EYE CARE</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-examination/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eye Examination</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-facts/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eye Facts</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-health/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eye Health</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/news/\" rel=\"category tag\">News</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/workplace-eyecare/\" rel=\"category tag\">Workplace eyecare</a></span> · </div></div><div class=\"post-1301 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-eye-care category-eye-examination category-eye-health category-eye-injury category-news category-workplace-eyecare entry\"><h2 class=\"entry-title\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/why-you-need-regular-eye-exams/\" rel=\"bookmark\">Why you need regular eye exams…</a></h2> \n<div class=\"post-info\"><span class=\"date published time\" title=\"2015-04-29T15:18:26+00:00\">29/04/2015</span>  by <span class=\"author vcard\"><span class=\"fn\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/author/admin/\" rel=\"author\">admin</a></span></span> ·  </div><div class=\"entry-content\"><p>Here at Campuspecs, your <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/our-location/\">independent Auckland optometry practice</a>, we know the benefits you will receive from regular eye exams, but do you?</p>\n<p><strong>You only have one pair of eyes and it’s really important to look after them and get them checked regularly. Here’s a list of reasons why…</strong></p>\n<ol>\n<li>Many serious eye diseases show no signs or symptoms. A full eye examination can pick up early signs of these eye conditions, including glaucoma, diabetic eye disease or macular degeneration.</li>\n<li>As with many health issues, the earlier a problem with your eyes is detected the more likely it is that it can be successfully treated. Around 80% of all eye conditions are preventable or curable.</li>\n<li>Having your eyes examined regularly, and picking up any problems can help lessen your risk of accidents, be they from, driving, cycling or falling.</li>\n<li>A regular eye exam can increase your productivity. Research cited by the American Optometric Association found that even a minor mis-correction increases the time to complete tasks by 9% and errors by 40%. If you are employer, here at Campuspecs we are able to tailor a <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/workplace-eyecare/\">workplace eye care package</a> to suit your needs and your budget. If you’re an employee tell your boss about it!</li>\n</ol>\n<p>We have invested in leading edge technology so you’ll see clearly, we’re the first optometry practice in New Zealand to utilise the NIDEK Optical Path Difference Scanning System, as part of your eye examination.</p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-1304\" src=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/EyeExam.jpg\" alt=\"EyeExam\" width=\"899\" height=\"713\"></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>When you visit Campuspecs for your eye exam, you’ll meet our optometrist Lisa. Lisa is responsible for everything to do with examining your eyes. She performs general eye examinations including checking your prescription (glasses and contacts), eye health and eye pressure. Lisa is a therapeutically qualified optometrist, able to prescribe medicated eye drops for certain eye conditions. She interprets all of the data gathered, and is able to advise on certain eye therapies, and conduct referrals for more serious eye conditions.</p>\n<p>Because we know how important a regular eye exam is, and because we love our locals… <em><strong>Until the end of May, if you live in Auckland, we’re offering you a full, comprehensive eye examination completely FREE. Includes retinal photo, visual field screening &amp; intra-ocular pressure check.</strong></em></p>\n<p>Check out the offer <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/eye-exam-deal/\">HERE.</a></p>\n</div><div class=\"post-meta\"><span class=\"categories\">Filed Under: <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-care/\" rel=\"category tag\">EYE CARE</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-examination/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eye Examination</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-health/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eye Health</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-injury/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eye Injury</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/news/\" rel=\"category tag\">News</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/workplace-eyecare/\" rel=\"category tag\">Workplace eyecare</a></span> · </div></div><div class=\"post-1297 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-eye-care category-eye-examination category-eye-facts category-eye-health category-eye-injury category-eyewear category-make-up category-news category-sunglasses category-uvb-protection entry\"><h2 class=\"entry-title\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/breaking-bad-habits-tips-on-how-to-improve-your-eye-health-from-your-auckland-optometrist/\" rel=\"bookmark\">Breaking Bad Habits… Tips on how to improve your eye health from your Auckland Optometrist</a></h2> \n<div class=\"post-info\"><span class=\"date published time\" title=\"2015-04-22T20:41:10+00:00\">22/04/2015</span>  by <span class=\"author vcard\"><span class=\"fn\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/author/admin/\" rel=\"author\">admin</a></span></span> ·  </div><div class=\"entry-content\"><p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-1260\" src=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Eyes.jpg\" alt=\"Eyes\" width=\"900\" height=\"307\"></p>\n<p>Here at Campuspecs, your <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/our-location/\">independent Auckland optometry practice</a>,we know how easy it is to fall into bad habits, but here are a few we want you to break, so you can improve your overall eye health.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Not wearing your sunglasses or specs</strong> – Excessive squinting from not wearing your glasses can lead to eyestrain, and pain. Your sunglasses block harmful UV&nbsp; and HEV rays, wear them even on an overcast day, go A-list!</li>\n<li><strong>Not getting enough sleep</strong> – Lack of sleep can cause red, bloodshot, dry, twitching eyes, and blurred vision. So settle down for some shut eye…</li>\n<li><strong>Making up… Sometimes</strong> – Just be careful of how you use make up. Tightlining, an eyeliner technique where make-up is applied to the inner rim of the eyelids could lead to eye disease. A recent Canadian study suggests that people should think twice before putting make-up so close to their eye’s tear rims. Read more <a href=\"http://www.stuff.co.nz/life-style/beauty/67588151/the-eyeliner-technique-that-could-lead-to-eye-disease\" target=\"_blank\">HERE</a>.</li>\n<li><strong>A bad diet</strong> –&nbsp; Vitamins, minerals and carotenoids found in many fruits, vegetables and other wholesome foods can help protect your sight and keep your eyes healthy. Check out this back article – <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/a-feast-for-your-eyes/\">A Feast for Your Eyes</a>.</li>\n<li><strong>Not using protective eyewear</strong> – We’re not just talking about the workplace. Many eye injuries happen at home from household and maintenance chores. Potential hazards range from being exposed to chemical cleaning products to mowing the lawn. So think safety!</li>\n<li><strong>Not following the 20-20-20 rule</strong> – find out what this is <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/give-your-eyes-a-workout/\">HERE</a>.</li>\n<li><strong>Not drinking enough water</strong> – Eye related symptoms from dehydration include dryness, redness and puffiness. Yes that’s why your eyes feel gritty after being exposed to the dry cabin air on a long haul flight!</li>\n<li><strong>Smoking</strong> – We don’t need to tell you that smoking is bad for your health, but because it’s our business we will tell you how smoking can affect your eye health. Research has linked smoking to cataracts, macular degeneration and other eye diseases. Smokers are four times more likely to go blind than non smokers.</li>\n<li><strong>Not coming to see us</strong> – That’s a seriously bad habit! Not only would we love to see you just to say hi, but a regular eye exam can often detect vision problems, eye disease and more general health issues before you’re aware or experiencing any symptoms.</li>\n</ul>\n</div><div class=\"post-meta\"><span class=\"categories\">Filed Under: <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-care/\" rel=\"category tag\">EYE CARE</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-examination/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eye Examination</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-facts/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eye Facts</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-health/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eye Health</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-injury/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eye Injury</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eyewear/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eyewear</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/make-up/\" rel=\"category tag\">Make Up</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/news/\" rel=\"category tag\">News</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/sunglasses/\" rel=\"category tag\">Sunglasses</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/uvb-protection/\" rel=\"category tag\">UVB protection</a></span> · </div></div><div class=\"post-1294 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-beauty category-eye-examination category-eye-wear category-eyewear category-fashion category-news entry\"><h2 class=\"entry-title\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/getting-in-the-right-frame-of-mind/\" rel=\"bookmark\">Getting in the right frame of mind.</a></h2> \n<div class=\"post-info\"><span class=\"date published time\" title=\"2015-04-11T04:25:12+00:00\">11/04/2015</span>  by <span class=\"author vcard\"><span class=\"fn\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/author/admin/\" rel=\"author\">admin</a></span></span> ·  </div><div class=\"entry-content\"><p>Here at Campuspecs, your <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/our-location/\">independent Auckland optometry practice</a>, we’re well aware that many of you would rather have 20/20 vision without the use of artificial aids. We know that investing in your perfect eyewear is sometimes a necessary purchase, yet not always something that you’d like to be spending your money on.</p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-1295\" src=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Screen-Shot-2015-04-11-at-4.22.03-am.png\" alt=\"Screen Shot 2015-04-11 at 4.22.03 am\" width=\"637\" height=\"319\"></p>\n<p>We’ve made it easier for you to see what your investment is likely to be with our eyewear menu…</p>\n<hr>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h1 style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>EYEWEAR MENU</strong></h1>\n<hr>\n<h1 style=\"text-align: center;\"></h1>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Frames</strong> — from <strong>$69</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Complete Specs</strong> — from <strong>$200</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em>includes standard single vision, anti-reflective lenses</em></p>\n<hr>\n<h3 style=\"text-align: center;\">OPTIONAL UPGRADES<em><br>\n</em></h3>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Thin Lenses</strong> (1.61) — <strong>$60</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Extra Thin Lenses</strong> (1.67) — <strong>$90</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Super Thin Lenses</strong> (1.74) — <strong>$120</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">♦♦♦</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Bifocal Lenses</strong> — <strong>$120</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Occupational Lenses</strong> — <strong>$140</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Progressive Lenses</strong> — <strong>$220</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">♦♦♦</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Tint &amp; UV</strong> — <strong>$60</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Polarising</strong> — <strong>$120</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Photochromic</strong> — <strong>$160</strong></p>\n<hr>\n<p><em><strong>We’ve also put together a list of our top tips that will help get you in the frame of mind to make the most of the experience of choosing your new specs at Campuspecs:</strong></em></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Inspiration from your icons…</strong> Before you come for your appointment take a look at your favourite actors, singers and celebrities. See what styles, shapes and colours they’re wearing and whether you think you’d like something similar.</li>\n<li><strong>Don’t rush a good thing…</strong> You don’t have to choose your specs the day you come for your eye exam. Have a chat with Bernice, your dispensing optician, she’ll be able to show you some options to consider, bring a friend and get their opinion too.</li>\n<li><strong>Get groomed…</strong> Try to tie in selection of your new frames with a trip to the hair salon. If you feel great about your hair, you’ll automatically feel better about trying on your specs.</li>\n<li><strong>Frock up or wear your party pants…</strong> If you wear an outfit you feel great in and that shows off your personal style, it will make frame selection a whole lot easier.</li>\n<li><strong>Trust us…</strong> At Campuspecs, we’re here to help you choose eyewear that will help you look and feel great, it’s something we do everyday, so we know a fair bit about choosing <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/frames-for-faces/\">frames to suit your face shape</a> and skin tone.</li>\n</ul>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">\n</p></div><div class=\"post-meta\"><span class=\"categories\">Filed Under: <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/beauty/\" rel=\"category tag\">Beauty</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-examination/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eye Examination</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-wear/\" rel=\"category tag\">EYE WEAR</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eyewear/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eyewear</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/fashion/\" rel=\"category tag\">Fashion</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/news/\" rel=\"category tag\">News</a></span> · </div></div><div class=\"post-1177 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-current-offers category-eye-care category-eye-examination category-news category-promotions entry\"><h2 class=\"entry-title\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/eye-exam-deal/\" rel=\"bookmark\">Eye Exam Deal</a></h2> \n<div class=\"post-info\"><span class=\"date published time\" title=\"2015-03-31T16:08:00+00:00\">31/03/2015</span>  by <span class=\"author vcard\"><span class=\"fn\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/author/admin/\" rel=\"author\">admin</a></span></span> ·  </div><div class=\"entry-content\"><p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-1289\" src=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/SliderCampus_Offers_1_Apr_May.jpg\" alt=\"SliderCampus_Offers_1_Apr_May\" width=\"960\" height=\"380\"></p>\n<p>We love being part of Auckland’s heart – just mention this offer and get a full, comprehensive eye examination completely FREE. Includes retinal photo, visual field screening &amp; intra-ocular pressure check.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>One eye exam per person</li>\n<li>Must be booked before 31/06/2015</li>\n</ul>\n</div><div class=\"post-meta\"><span class=\"categories\">Filed Under: <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/current-offers/\" rel=\"category tag\">CURRENT OFFERS</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-care/\" rel=\"category tag\">EYE CARE</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-examination/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eye Examination</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/news/\" rel=\"category tag\">News</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/promotions/\" rel=\"category tag\">Promotions</a></span> · </div></div><div class=\"post-1264 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-eye-wear category-eyewear category-fashion category-make-up category-news entry\"><h2 class=\"entry-title\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/making-up-is-not-so-hard-to-do/\" rel=\"bookmark\">Making up is not so hard to do…</a></h2> \n<div class=\"post-info\"><span class=\"date published time\" title=\"2015-03-10T17:23:41+00:00\">10/03/2015</span>  by <span class=\"author vcard\"><span class=\"fn\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/author/admin/\" rel=\"author\">admin</a></span></span> ·  </div><div class=\"entry-content\"><p><img class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-1265\" src=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Makeup__Specs.jpg\" alt=\"Makeup__Specs\" width=\"400\" height=\"267\">Here at Campuspecs, your <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/our-location/\">independent Auckland optometry practice</a>, we know that your glasses can have a huge impact on your appearance, there’s nothing we like more than helping you discover the perfect frames to fit your face and complexion.</p>\n<p>When you wear glasses – it draws attention to your face and more specifically your eyes, for that reason when you are a glasses wearer there are a few things you might want to consider when applying your makeup.</p>\n<p>Here is a list of tips, in no particular order, to ensure your “making up” is not so hard to do…</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Frames can cast a shadow under your eye. Use a yellow-toned concealer to colour correct this.</li>\n<li>Your brows are really important, as these will actually frame your frames, so use a pencil, gel or powder to tame and define your brows. If you get your eyebrows professionally shaped, make sure your therapist knows what your frames are like.</li>\n<li>Keep it simple… There’s generally a lot going on if you’re a glasses wearer, so keep it simple. Think about the colour of your frames when choosing an eyeshadow, a neutral pallet will always work well. Make sure you keep your eyeshadow within the frame line.</li>\n<li>Don’t avoid the mascara, this will highlight your eyes and really bring them out from behind your glasses. If you want to avoid your mascara smudging against your specs, you may find that wearing a waterproof mascara will help. An eyelash curler will also help to open your eyes behind your specs.</li>\n<li>Get bright with the lips. It doesn’t matter whether you choose red, bright pink, coral or violet. A pop of colour will ensure you look amazing! It will balance out your neutral eye makeup, and will also have the same effect of balancing out your features if your frames are coloured or thicker in style.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</div><div class=\"post-meta\"><span class=\"categories\">Filed Under: <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-wear/\" rel=\"category tag\">EYE WEAR</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eyewear/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eyewear</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/fashion/\" rel=\"category tag\">Fashion</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/make-up/\" rel=\"category tag\">Make Up</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/news/\" rel=\"category tag\">News</a></span> · </div></div><div class=\"post-1256 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-eye-examination category-eye-health category-news category-technology category-workplace-eyecare entry\"><h2 class=\"entry-title\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/give-your-eyes-a-workout/\" rel=\"bookmark\">Give your eyes a workout.</a></h2> \n<div class=\"post-info\"><span class=\"date published time\" title=\"2015-02-22T13:04:30+00:00\">22/02/2015</span>  by <span class=\"author vcard\"><span class=\"fn\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/author/admin/\" rel=\"author\">admin</a></span></span> ·  </div><div class=\"entry-content\"><p>Here at Campuspecs, your independent Auckland optometry practice, we’ve posted before about Computer Vision Syndrome before… read it <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/do-you-suffer-from-computer-vision-syndrome/\"><em><strong>here.</strong></em></a></p>\n<p>Do you check your phone before you even get out of bed in the morning? Do you head to study or work where you’ll spend most of the day at a computer? When you get home in the evenings are you sat watching the TV whilst browsing the internet on your tablet?</p>\n<p>With more and more of us admitting we couldn’t last a day without being connected, we thought it was a good time to revisit the subject of digital eye strain.</p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-1260\" src=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Eyes.jpg\" alt=\"Eyes\" width=\"900\" height=\"307\"></p>\n<h3><strong>The easiest way to address digital eye strain is to give your eyes a short workout.&nbsp;</strong></h3>\n<p>There are two good ways to do this that you can put into practice easily and immediately.</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Firstly, blink more often, blinking moistens your eyes to prevent dryness and irritation. It’s commonly known that people blink less frequently, when working at a computer. Tears coating the eye evaporate more rapidly during long non-blinking phases and this can cause dry eyes. Here is a specific exercise to reduce your risk of dry eyes during computer use. Every 20 minutes, blink 10 times by closing your eyes as if you’re falling asleep. This will stimulate lubrication of your eyes.</li>\n<li>The second way we would recommend to give your eyes a workout to help avoid or resolve digital eye strain is to follow the simple three step “20-20-20 Rule”</li>\n</ol>\n<ul>\n<li>Every 20 minutes give your eyes a break by taking them off your computer.</li>\n<li>Look at something at least 20 feet away.</li>\n<li>For at least 20 seconds.</li>\n</ul>\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><em>Following these three steps will engage your distance vision and help your eyes to reset and refocus.</em></p>\n<hr>\n<p>Remember that having a regular comprehensive eye exam is the most important thing you can do to prevent or treat computer vision problems. When you’re talking to Lisa, our optometrist, be sure to tell her how often you use a computer or device at work and at home.</p>\n</div><div class=\"post-meta\"><span class=\"categories\">Filed Under: <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-examination/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eye Examination</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-health/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eye Health</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/news/\" rel=\"category tag\">News</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/technology/\" rel=\"category tag\">Technology</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/workplace-eyecare/\" rel=\"category tag\">Workplace eyecare</a></span> · </div></div><div class=\"post-1251 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-eye-wear category-eyewear category-fashion category-news category-store-updates entry\"><h2 class=\"entry-title\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/your-auckland-optometrists-encourage-you-to-love-what-you-look-through/\" rel=\"bookmark\">Your Auckland Optometrists encourage you to “Love What You Look Through”</a></h2> \n<div class=\"post-info\"><span class=\"date published time\" title=\"2015-02-01T13:08:11+00:00\">01/02/2015</span>  by <span class=\"author vcard\"><span class=\"fn\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/author/admin/\" rel=\"author\">admin</a></span></span> ·  </div><div class=\"entry-content\"><p>We want you to “Love What You Look Through”! As one of Aucklands leading Independent Optometrists &amp; Eyewear Specialists we know how important it is for you to not only see clearly but also feel great. That is why we offer such a wide range of styles and colours!</p>\n<p>With frames starting at $69, Campuspecs believes that fashion doesn’t need to break the bank. Many of the brands stocked here, including Chevrolet, XVO and Modem Girl are new to New Zealand, and the broad range of frames, in diverse colours and materials mean every client has a choice of over 350 options when selecting their new frames.</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/about-us/meet-the-team/\">Lisa and Bernice</a> our Optometrist and Managing Dispensing Optician respectively, would love to see you, they can help you look great and see better, they can help you select frames that will suit your face shape (or if you would like to do some research before coming in to see us take a look at <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/frames-for-faces/\" target=\"_blank\">this article</a>), plus if you would like some inspiration on hot eyewear trends for 2015, check out this <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/hot-eyewear-trends-for-2015/\" target=\"_blank\">article</a>. We’ve introduced the latest eye care technology and frame designs to ensure you look, and see, the best you can. We can also help you with contact lenses, we have a great selection of competitively priced daily and monthly disposables.</p>\n<p><strong>During February and March, if you spend over $400 on new eyewear, we’ll give you $100 off.</strong></p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-1245\" src=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/SliderCampus_Offers_FebMar.jpg\" alt=\"SliderCampus_Offers_FebMar\" width=\"960\" height=\"380\"></p>\n<p>We want you to be able to see our pricing clearly, that’s why we’ve produced your “Eyewear Menu”…</p>\n<hr>\n<h1 style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>YOUR EYEWEAR MENU</strong></h1>\n<hr>\n<h1 style=\"text-align: center;\"></h1>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Frames</strong> — from <strong>$69</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Complete Specs</strong> — from <strong>$200</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em>includes standard single vision, anti-reflective lenses</em></p>\n<hr>\n<h3 style=\"text-align: center;\">OPTIONAL UPGRADES<em><br>\n</em></h3>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Thin Lenses</strong> (1.61) — <strong>$60</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Extra Thin Lenses</strong> (1.67) — <strong>$90</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Super Thin Lenses</strong> (1.74) — <strong>$120</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">♦♦♦</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Bifocal Lenses</strong> — <strong>$120</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Occupational Lenses</strong> — <strong>$140</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Progressive Lenses</strong> — <strong>$220</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">♦♦♦</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Tint &amp; UV</strong> — <strong>$60</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Polarising</strong> — <strong>$120</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Photochromic</strong> — <strong>$160</strong></p>\n<hr>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">\n</p></div><div class=\"post-meta\"><span class=\"categories\">Filed Under: <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-wear/\" rel=\"category tag\">EYE WEAR</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eyewear/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eyewear</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/fashion/\" rel=\"category tag\">Fashion</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/news/\" rel=\"category tag\">News</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/store-updates/\" rel=\"category tag\">Store Updates</a></span> · </div></div><div class=\"post-1240 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-eye-care category-eye-examination category-eye-health category-eyewear category-news category-uncategorized entry\"><h2 class=\"entry-title\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/focussing-on-student-eyecare-in-auckland/\" rel=\"bookmark\">Focussing On Student Eyecare in Auckland</a></h2> \n<div class=\"post-info\"><span class=\"date published time\" title=\"2015-01-28T15:14:19+00:00\">28/01/2015</span>  by <span class=\"author vcard\"><span class=\"fn\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/author/admin/\" rel=\"author\">admin</a></span></span> ·  </div><div class=\"entry-content\"><p><img class=\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-1243\" src=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/Student-300x200.jpg\" alt=\"Student\" width=\"300\" height=\"200\">As your Auckland CBD optometrists, with only just over a month until the start of Semester 1, we’d like to ask you to focus on something really important, and that’s to make sure your eyes are in tip top condition for the year ahead.</p>\n<p>To that end, we’re offering students the chance to take advantage of a free eye exam for the week beginning 26th January, 2015, you can <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/appointment-enquiry/\" target=\"_blank\">book online</a>, to take advantage of this offer.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>We were the first practice in New Zealand with a primary objective of offering eyecare and optical glasses for students, and helping you maximise your ability to learn has always been important to us. As the city’s only optometry practice offering first-rate eye care specifically tailored for tertiary students, we make it easy for you to take advantage of first rate eye care, benefits include extended opening hours and generous student discounts. We’re located just a short walk from both the University of Auckland and Auckland University of Technology. We are also official Eyecare partners with <a href=\"http://www.studentassist.co.nz/\" target=\"_blank\">Studentsafe.</a></p>\n<p>Our practice focuses on affordable fashion eyewear, with frames starting at $69. Many of our designer brands, including Chevrolet, XVO and Modem Girl are new to New Zealand. The broad range of frames, in diverse colours and materials mean you have a choice of over 350 options when selecting your new frames.</p>\n<p>Campuspecs has invested in leading edge technology so you’ll see clearly, we’re the first optometry practice in New Zealand to utilise the NIDEK Optical Path Difference Scanning System.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</div><div class=\"post-meta\"><span class=\"categories\">Filed Under: <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-care/\" rel=\"category tag\">EYE CARE</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-examination/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eye Examination</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-health/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eye Health</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eyewear/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eyewear</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/news/\" rel=\"category tag\">News</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/uncategorized/\" rel=\"category tag\">Uncategorized</a></span> · </div></div><div class=\"navigation\"><div class=\"pagination-next alignright\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/news/page/2/\">Next Page»</a></div></div></div></div></div></div>\";s:11:\"panels_info\";a:5:{s:5:\"class\";s:14:\"WP_Widget_Text\";s:4:\"grid\";i:0;s:4:\"cell\";i:0;s:2:\"id\";i:0;s:5:\"style\";a:2:{s:27:\"background_image_attachment\";b:0;s:18:\"background_display\";s:4:\"tile\";}}s:6:\"filter\";b:0;}i:1;a:4:{s:5:\"title\";s:0:\"\";s:12:\"unitegallery\";s:1:\"1\";s:16:\"unitegallery_cat\";s:1:\"1\";s:11:\"panels_info\";a:6:{s:5:\"class\";s:19:\"UniteGallery_Widget\";s:3:\"raw\";b:0;s:4:\"grid\";i:1;s:4:\"cell\";i:0;s:2:\"id\";i:1;s:5:\"style\";a:1:{s:18:\"background_display\";s:4:\"tile\";}}}}s:5:\"grids\";a:2:{i:0;a:2:{s:5:\"cells\";i:1;s:5:\"style\";a:0:{}}i:1;a:2:{s:5:\"cells\";i:1;s:5:\"style\";a:2:{s:23:\"background_image_repeat\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"no_margin\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:10:\"grid_cells\";a:2:{i:0;a:2:{s:4:\"grid\";i:0;s:6:\"weight\";i:1;}i:1;a:2:{s:4:\"grid\";i:1;s:6:\"weight\";i:1;}}}'),(839,202,'panels_data','a:3:{s:7:\"widgets\";a:2:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"title\";s:0:\"\";s:4:\"text\";s:37840:\"<div id=\"inner\"><div class=\"wrap\"><div id=\"content-sidebar-wrap\"><div id=\"content\" class=\"hfeed\"><div class=\"post-1316 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-eye-care category-eye-examination category-eye-facts category-eye-health category-news entry\"><h2 class=\"entry-title\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/10-signs-that-you-need-to-book-an-eye-exam/\" rel=\"bookmark\">10 signs that you need to book an eye exam</a></h2> \n<div class=\"post-info\"><span class=\"date published time\" title=\"2015-06-07T18:00:53+00:00\">07/06/2015</span>  by <span class=\"author vcard\"><span class=\"fn\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/author/admin/\" rel=\"author\">admin</a></span></span> ·  </div><div class=\"entry-content\"><p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-1318\" src=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/Screen-Shot-2015-06-07-at-5.54.24-pm.png\" alt=\"Screen Shot 2015-06-07 at 5.54.24 pm\" width=\"950\" height=\"321\"></p>\n<p>Here at Campuspecs, your <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/our-location/\">Auckland CBD optometrist</a>, we recommend you have regular eye exams; after all you only have one pair of eyes so keeping them healthy is really important. Not only that but a simple eye test can do more than assess your sight; warning signs for a range of life threatening illnesses can be detected in the inner workings of the eye.</p>\n<p>So how regular is regular? Well as a general rule of thumb we recommend adults have eye exams approximately every two years, but your personal requirement can also depend on a few varying factors…</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Your age</li>\n<li>Whether you currently wear corrective lenses</li>\n<li>Whether you have a family history of glaucoma or macular degeneration</li>\n<li>Whether you suffer from diabetes, an existing eye disorder; or have had eye surgery or suffered a trauma to the eye.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Nevertheless, there are often signs and symptoms associated with a more urgent requirement to visit your optometrist. So here are a few signs that should serve as a reminder to make an immediate appointment for your next eye examination.</p>\n<ol>\n<li>You can’t remember the last time you visited an optometrist</li>\n<li>You have begun suffering from blurred vision or are having problems focusing</li>\n<li>You are seeing spots, flashes of light, or floaters</li>\n<li>Your eyes are dry, red or itchy</li>\n<li>You’re getting frequent headaches</li>\n<li>Your eyes are not adjusting to different levels of light, and you’re finding it difficult to see in the dark; or your eyes are sensitive to light</li>\n<li>You’re squinting</li>\n<li>You’re suffering from motion sickness or dizziness</li>\n<li>You feel you need longer arms! i.e. You’re holding reading material further and further away from you</li>\n<li>You’re suffering from or have recently suffered from an eye infection</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Don’t forget if you’re an Auckland local, who hasn’t yet taken up the Campuspecs offer of a FREE, comprehensive eye examination. We have extended this offer until the end of June! Your complimentary eye exam will include retinal photo, visual field screening &amp; intra-ocular pressure check.</p>\n<p><strong><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/appointment-enquiry/\">BOOK HERE</a></strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</div><div class=\"post-meta\"><span class=\"categories\">Filed Under: <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-care/\" rel=\"category tag\">EYE CARE</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-examination/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eye Examination</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-facts/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eye Facts</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-health/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eye Health</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/news/\" rel=\"category tag\">News</a></span> · </div></div><div class=\"post-1309 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-current-offers category-eye-care category-eye-examination category-eye-facts category-eye-health category-news category-workplace-eyecare entry\"><h2 class=\"entry-title\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/your-optometrist-loving-local-auckland-eyes-for-longer/\" rel=\"bookmark\">Your optometrist loving local Auckland eyes for longer…</a></h2> \n<div class=\"post-info\"><span class=\"date published time\" title=\"2015-06-01T12:55:27+00:00\">01/06/2015</span>  by <span class=\"author vcard\"><span class=\"fn\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/author/admin/\" rel=\"author\">admin</a></span></span> ·  </div><div class=\"entry-content\"><p>We have great news for all you Auckland locals, who haven’t yet taken up the Campuspecs offer of a FREE, comprehensive eye examination. We are extending this offer until the end of June!</p>\n<p>Your eye exam will include retinal photo, visual field screening &amp; intra-ocular pressure check.</p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-1289\" src=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/SliderCampus_Offers_1_Apr_May.jpg\" alt=\"SliderCampus_Offers_1_Apr_May\" width=\"960\" height=\"380\"></p>\n<p>You can find out full details <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/eye-exam-deal/\">HERE</a>.</p>\n<p>When you visit Campuspecs for your eye exam, you’ll meet our optometrist Lisa. Lisa is responsible for everything to do with examining your eyes. She performs general eye examinations including checking your prescription (glasses and contacts), eye health and eye pressure. Lisa is a therapeutically qualified optometrist, able to prescribe medicated eye drops for certain eye conditions. She interprets all of the data gathered, and is able to advise on certain eye therapies, and conduct referrals for more serious eye conditions.</p>\n<p><strong>Four reasons why it’s important to have a regular eye exam…</strong></p>\n<ol>\n<li>Many serious eye diseases show no signs or symptoms. A full eye examination can pick up early signs of these eye conditions, including glaucoma, diabetic eye disease or macular degeneration.</li>\n<li>As with many health issues, the earlier a problem with your eyes is detected the more likely it is that it can be successfully treated. Around 80% of all eye conditions are preventable or curable.</li>\n<li>Having your eyes examined regularly, and picking up any problems can help lessen your risk of accidents, be they from, driving, cycling or falling.</li>\n<li>A regular eye exam can increase your productivity. Research cited by the American Optometric Association found that even a minor mis-correction increases the time to complete tasks by 9% and errors by 40%. If you are employer, here at Campuspecs we are able to tailor a <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/workplace-eyecare/\">workplace eye care package</a> to suit your needs and your budget. If you’re an employee tell your boss about it!</li>\n</ol>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</div><div class=\"post-meta\"><span class=\"categories\">Filed Under: <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/current-offers/\" rel=\"category tag\">CURRENT OFFERS</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-care/\" rel=\"category tag\">EYE CARE</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-examination/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eye Examination</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-facts/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eye Facts</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-health/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eye Health</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/news/\" rel=\"category tag\">News</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/workplace-eyecare/\" rel=\"category tag\">Workplace eyecare</a></span> · </div></div><div class=\"post-1301 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-eye-care category-eye-examination category-eye-health category-eye-injury category-news category-workplace-eyecare entry\"><h2 class=\"entry-title\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/why-you-need-regular-eye-exams/\" rel=\"bookmark\">Why you need regular eye exams…</a></h2> \n<div class=\"post-info\"><span class=\"date published time\" title=\"2015-04-29T15:18:26+00:00\">29/04/2015</span>  by <span class=\"author vcard\"><span class=\"fn\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/author/admin/\" rel=\"author\">admin</a></span></span> ·  </div><div class=\"entry-content\"><p>Here at Campuspecs, your <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/our-location/\">independent Auckland optometry practice</a>, we know the benefits you will receive from regular eye exams, but do you?</p>\n<p><strong>You only have one pair of eyes and it’s really important to look after them and get them checked regularly. Here’s a list of reasons why…</strong></p>\n<ol>\n<li>Many serious eye diseases show no signs or symptoms. A full eye examination can pick up early signs of these eye conditions, including glaucoma, diabetic eye disease or macular degeneration.</li>\n<li>As with many health issues, the earlier a problem with your eyes is detected the more likely it is that it can be successfully treated. Around 80% of all eye conditions are preventable or curable.</li>\n<li>Having your eyes examined regularly, and picking up any problems can help lessen your risk of accidents, be they from, driving, cycling or falling.</li>\n<li>A regular eye exam can increase your productivity. Research cited by the American Optometric Association found that even a minor mis-correction increases the time to complete tasks by 9% and errors by 40%. If you are employer, here at Campuspecs we are able to tailor a <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/workplace-eyecare/\">workplace eye care package</a> to suit your needs and your budget. If you’re an employee tell your boss about it!</li>\n</ol>\n<p>We have invested in leading edge technology so you’ll see clearly, we’re the first optometry practice in New Zealand to utilise the NIDEK Optical Path Difference Scanning System, as part of your eye examination.</p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-1304\" src=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/EyeExam.jpg\" alt=\"EyeExam\" width=\"899\" height=\"713\"></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>When you visit Campuspecs for your eye exam, you’ll meet our optometrist Lisa. Lisa is responsible for everything to do with examining your eyes. She performs general eye examinations including checking your prescription (glasses and contacts), eye health and eye pressure. Lisa is a therapeutically qualified optometrist, able to prescribe medicated eye drops for certain eye conditions. She interprets all of the data gathered, and is able to advise on certain eye therapies, and conduct referrals for more serious eye conditions.</p>\n<p>Because we know how important a regular eye exam is, and because we love our locals… <em><strong>Until the end of May, if you live in Auckland, we’re offering you a full, comprehensive eye examination completely FREE. Includes retinal photo, visual field screening &amp; intra-ocular pressure check.</strong></em></p>\n<p>Check out the offer <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/eye-exam-deal/\">HERE.</a></p>\n</div><div class=\"post-meta\"><span class=\"categories\">Filed Under: <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-care/\" rel=\"category tag\">EYE CARE</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-examination/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eye Examination</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-health/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eye Health</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-injury/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eye Injury</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/news/\" rel=\"category tag\">News</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/workplace-eyecare/\" rel=\"category tag\">Workplace eyecare</a></span> · </div></div><div class=\"post-1297 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-eye-care category-eye-examination category-eye-facts category-eye-health category-eye-injury category-eyewear category-make-up category-news category-sunglasses category-uvb-protection entry\"><h2 class=\"entry-title\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/breaking-bad-habits-tips-on-how-to-improve-your-eye-health-from-your-auckland-optometrist/\" rel=\"bookmark\">Breaking Bad Habits… Tips on how to improve your eye health from your Auckland Optometrist</a></h2> \n<div class=\"post-info\"><span class=\"date published time\" title=\"2015-04-22T20:41:10+00:00\">22/04/2015</span>  by <span class=\"author vcard\"><span class=\"fn\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/author/admin/\" rel=\"author\">admin</a></span></span> ·  </div><div class=\"entry-content\"><p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-1260\" src=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Eyes.jpg\" alt=\"Eyes\" width=\"900\" height=\"307\"></p>\n<p>Here at Campuspecs, your <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/our-location/\">independent Auckland optometry practice</a>,we know how easy it is to fall into bad habits, but here are a few we want you to break, so you can improve your overall eye health.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Not wearing your sunglasses or specs</strong> – Excessive squinting from not wearing your glasses can lead to eyestrain, and pain. Your sunglasses block harmful UV&nbsp; and HEV rays, wear them even on an overcast day, go A-list!</li>\n<li><strong>Not getting enough sleep</strong> – Lack of sleep can cause red, bloodshot, dry, twitching eyes, and blurred vision. So settle down for some shut eye…</li>\n<li><strong>Making up… Sometimes</strong> – Just be careful of how you use make up. Tightlining, an eyeliner technique where make-up is applied to the inner rim of the eyelids could lead to eye disease. A recent Canadian study suggests that people should think twice before putting make-up so close to their eye’s tear rims. Read more <a href=\"http://www.stuff.co.nz/life-style/beauty/67588151/the-eyeliner-technique-that-could-lead-to-eye-disease\" target=\"_blank\">HERE</a>.</li>\n<li><strong>A bad diet</strong> –&nbsp; Vitamins, minerals and carotenoids found in many fruits, vegetables and other wholesome foods can help protect your sight and keep your eyes healthy. Check out this back article – <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/a-feast-for-your-eyes/\">A Feast for Your Eyes</a>.</li>\n<li><strong>Not using protective eyewear</strong> – We’re not just talking about the workplace. Many eye injuries happen at home from household and maintenance chores. Potential hazards range from being exposed to chemical cleaning products to mowing the lawn. So think safety!</li>\n<li><strong>Not following the 20-20-20 rule</strong> – find out what this is <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/give-your-eyes-a-workout/\">HERE</a>.</li>\n<li><strong>Not drinking enough water</strong> – Eye related symptoms from dehydration include dryness, redness and puffiness. Yes that’s why your eyes feel gritty after being exposed to the dry cabin air on a long haul flight!</li>\n<li><strong>Smoking</strong> – We don’t need to tell you that smoking is bad for your health, but because it’s our business we will tell you how smoking can affect your eye health. Research has linked smoking to cataracts, macular degeneration and other eye diseases. Smokers are four times more likely to go blind than non smokers.</li>\n<li><strong>Not coming to see us</strong> – That’s a seriously bad habit! Not only would we love to see you just to say hi, but a regular eye exam can often detect vision problems, eye disease and more general health issues before you’re aware or experiencing any symptoms.</li>\n</ul>\n</div><div class=\"post-meta\"><span class=\"categories\">Filed Under: <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-care/\" rel=\"category tag\">EYE CARE</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-examination/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eye Examination</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-facts/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eye Facts</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-health/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eye Health</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-injury/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eye Injury</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eyewear/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eyewear</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/make-up/\" rel=\"category tag\">Make Up</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/news/\" rel=\"category tag\">News</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/sunglasses/\" rel=\"category tag\">Sunglasses</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/uvb-protection/\" rel=\"category tag\">UVB protection</a></span> · </div></div><div class=\"post-1294 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-beauty category-eye-examination category-eye-wear category-eyewear category-fashion category-news entry\"><h2 class=\"entry-title\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/getting-in-the-right-frame-of-mind/\" rel=\"bookmark\">Getting in the right frame of mind.</a></h2> \n<div class=\"post-info\"><span class=\"date published time\" title=\"2015-04-11T04:25:12+00:00\">11/04/2015</span>  by <span class=\"author vcard\"><span class=\"fn\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/author/admin/\" rel=\"author\">admin</a></span></span> ·  </div><div class=\"entry-content\"><p>Here at Campuspecs, your <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/our-location/\">independent Auckland optometry practice</a>, we’re well aware that many of you would rather have 20/20 vision without the use of artificial aids. We know that investing in your perfect eyewear is sometimes a necessary purchase, yet not always something that you’d like to be spending your money on.</p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-1295\" src=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Screen-Shot-2015-04-11-at-4.22.03-am.png\" alt=\"Screen Shot 2015-04-11 at 4.22.03 am\" width=\"637\" height=\"319\"></p>\n<p>We’ve made it easier for you to see what your investment is likely to be with our eyewear menu…</p>\n<hr>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h1 style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>EYEWEAR MENU</strong></h1>\n<hr>\n<h1 style=\"text-align: center;\"></h1>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Frames</strong> — from <strong>$69</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Complete Specs</strong> — from <strong>$200</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em>includes standard single vision, anti-reflective lenses</em></p>\n<hr>\n<h3 style=\"text-align: center;\">OPTIONAL UPGRADES<em><br>\n</em></h3>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Thin Lenses</strong> (1.61) — <strong>$60</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Extra Thin Lenses</strong> (1.67) — <strong>$90</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Super Thin Lenses</strong> (1.74) — <strong>$120</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">♦♦♦</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Bifocal Lenses</strong> — <strong>$120</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Occupational Lenses</strong> — <strong>$140</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Progressive Lenses</strong> — <strong>$220</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">♦♦♦</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Tint &amp; UV</strong> — <strong>$60</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Polarising</strong> — <strong>$120</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Photochromic</strong> — <strong>$160</strong></p>\n<hr>\n<p><em><strong>We’ve also put together a list of our top tips that will help get you in the frame of mind to make the most of the experience of choosing your new specs at Campuspecs:</strong></em></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Inspiration from your icons…</strong> Before you come for your appointment take a look at your favourite actors, singers and celebrities. See what styles, shapes and colours they’re wearing and whether you think you’d like something similar.</li>\n<li><strong>Don’t rush a good thing…</strong> You don’t have to choose your specs the day you come for your eye exam. Have a chat with Bernice, your dispensing optician, she’ll be able to show you some options to consider, bring a friend and get their opinion too.</li>\n<li><strong>Get groomed…</strong> Try to tie in selection of your new frames with a trip to the hair salon. If you feel great about your hair, you’ll automatically feel better about trying on your specs.</li>\n<li><strong>Frock up or wear your party pants…</strong> If you wear an outfit you feel great in and that shows off your personal style, it will make frame selection a whole lot easier.</li>\n<li><strong>Trust us…</strong> At Campuspecs, we’re here to help you choose eyewear that will help you look and feel great, it’s something we do everyday, so we know a fair bit about choosing <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/frames-for-faces/\">frames to suit your face shape</a> and skin tone.</li>\n</ul>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">\n</p></div><div class=\"post-meta\"><span class=\"categories\">Filed Under: <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/beauty/\" rel=\"category tag\">Beauty</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-examination/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eye Examination</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-wear/\" rel=\"category tag\">EYE WEAR</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eyewear/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eyewear</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/fashion/\" rel=\"category tag\">Fashion</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/news/\" rel=\"category tag\">News</a></span> · </div></div><div class=\"post-1177 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-current-offers category-eye-care category-eye-examination category-news category-promotions entry\"><h2 class=\"entry-title\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/eye-exam-deal/\" rel=\"bookmark\">Eye Exam Deal</a></h2> \n<div class=\"post-info\"><span class=\"date published time\" title=\"2015-03-31T16:08:00+00:00\">31/03/2015</span>  by <span class=\"author vcard\"><span class=\"fn\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/author/admin/\" rel=\"author\">admin</a></span></span> ·  </div><div class=\"entry-content\"><p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-1289\" src=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/SliderCampus_Offers_1_Apr_May.jpg\" alt=\"SliderCampus_Offers_1_Apr_May\" width=\"960\" height=\"380\"></p>\n<p>We love being part of Auckland’s heart – just mention this offer and get a full, comprehensive eye examination completely FREE. Includes retinal photo, visual field screening &amp; intra-ocular pressure check.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>One eye exam per person</li>\n<li>Must be booked before 31/06/2015</li>\n</ul>\n</div><div class=\"post-meta\"><span class=\"categories\">Filed Under: <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/current-offers/\" rel=\"category tag\">CURRENT OFFERS</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-care/\" rel=\"category tag\">EYE CARE</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-examination/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eye Examination</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/news/\" rel=\"category tag\">News</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/promotions/\" rel=\"category tag\">Promotions</a></span> · </div></div><div class=\"post-1264 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-eye-wear category-eyewear category-fashion category-make-up category-news entry\"><h2 class=\"entry-title\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/making-up-is-not-so-hard-to-do/\" rel=\"bookmark\">Making up is not so hard to do…</a></h2> \n<div class=\"post-info\"><span class=\"date published time\" title=\"2015-03-10T17:23:41+00:00\">10/03/2015</span>  by <span class=\"author vcard\"><span class=\"fn\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/author/admin/\" rel=\"author\">admin</a></span></span> ·  </div><div class=\"entry-content\"><p><img class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-1265\" src=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Makeup__Specs.jpg\" alt=\"Makeup__Specs\" width=\"400\" height=\"267\">Here at Campuspecs, your <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/our-location/\">independent Auckland optometry practice</a>, we know that your glasses can have a huge impact on your appearance, there’s nothing we like more than helping you discover the perfect frames to fit your face and complexion.</p>\n<p>When you wear glasses – it draws attention to your face and more specifically your eyes, for that reason when you are a glasses wearer there are a few things you might want to consider when applying your makeup.</p>\n<p>Here is a list of tips, in no particular order, to ensure your “making up” is not so hard to do…</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Frames can cast a shadow under your eye. Use a yellow-toned concealer to colour correct this.</li>\n<li>Your brows are really important, as these will actually frame your frames, so use a pencil, gel or powder to tame and define your brows. If you get your eyebrows professionally shaped, make sure your therapist knows what your frames are like.</li>\n<li>Keep it simple… There’s generally a lot going on if you’re a glasses wearer, so keep it simple. Think about the colour of your frames when choosing an eyeshadow, a neutral pallet will always work well. Make sure you keep your eyeshadow within the frame line.</li>\n<li>Don’t avoid the mascara, this will highlight your eyes and really bring them out from behind your glasses. If you want to avoid your mascara smudging against your specs, you may find that wearing a waterproof mascara will help. An eyelash curler will also help to open your eyes behind your specs.</li>\n<li>Get bright with the lips. It doesn’t matter whether you choose red, bright pink, coral or violet. A pop of colour will ensure you look amazing! It will balance out your neutral eye makeup, and will also have the same effect of balancing out your features if your frames are coloured or thicker in style.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</div><div class=\"post-meta\"><span class=\"categories\">Filed Under: <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-wear/\" rel=\"category tag\">EYE WEAR</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eyewear/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eyewear</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/fashion/\" rel=\"category tag\">Fashion</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/make-up/\" rel=\"category tag\">Make Up</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/news/\" rel=\"category tag\">News</a></span> · </div></div><div class=\"post-1256 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-eye-examination category-eye-health category-news category-technology category-workplace-eyecare entry\"><h2 class=\"entry-title\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/give-your-eyes-a-workout/\" rel=\"bookmark\">Give your eyes a workout.</a></h2> \n<div class=\"post-info\"><span class=\"date published time\" title=\"2015-02-22T13:04:30+00:00\">22/02/2015</span>  by <span class=\"author vcard\"><span class=\"fn\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/author/admin/\" rel=\"author\">admin</a></span></span> ·  </div><div class=\"entry-content\"><p>Here at Campuspecs, your independent Auckland optometry practice, we’ve posted before about Computer Vision Syndrome before… read it <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/do-you-suffer-from-computer-vision-syndrome/\"><em><strong>here.</strong></em></a></p>\n<p>Do you check your phone before you even get out of bed in the morning? Do you head to study or work where you’ll spend most of the day at a computer? When you get home in the evenings are you sat watching the TV whilst browsing the internet on your tablet?</p>\n<p>With more and more of us admitting we couldn’t last a day without being connected, we thought it was a good time to revisit the subject of digital eye strain.</p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-1260\" src=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Eyes.jpg\" alt=\"Eyes\" width=\"900\" height=\"307\"></p>\n<h3><strong>The easiest way to address digital eye strain is to give your eyes a short workout.&nbsp;</strong></h3>\n<p>There are two good ways to do this that you can put into practice easily and immediately.</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Firstly, blink more often, blinking moistens your eyes to prevent dryness and irritation. It’s commonly known that people blink less frequently, when working at a computer. Tears coating the eye evaporate more rapidly during long non-blinking phases and this can cause dry eyes. Here is a specific exercise to reduce your risk of dry eyes during computer use. Every 20 minutes, blink 10 times by closing your eyes as if you’re falling asleep. This will stimulate lubrication of your eyes.</li>\n<li>The second way we would recommend to give your eyes a workout to help avoid or resolve digital eye strain is to follow the simple three step “20-20-20 Rule”</li>\n</ol>\n<ul>\n<li>Every 20 minutes give your eyes a break by taking them off your computer.</li>\n<li>Look at something at least 20 feet away.</li>\n<li>For at least 20 seconds.</li>\n</ul>\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><em>Following these three steps will engage your distance vision and help your eyes to reset and refocus.</em></p>\n<hr>\n<p>Remember that having a regular comprehensive eye exam is the most important thing you can do to prevent or treat computer vision problems. When you’re talking to Lisa, our optometrist, be sure to tell her how often you use a computer or device at work and at home.</p>\n</div><div class=\"post-meta\"><span class=\"categories\">Filed Under: <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-examination/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eye Examination</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-health/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eye Health</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/news/\" rel=\"category tag\">News</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/technology/\" rel=\"category tag\">Technology</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/workplace-eyecare/\" rel=\"category tag\">Workplace eyecare</a></span> · </div></div><div class=\"post-1251 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-eye-wear category-eyewear category-fashion category-news category-store-updates entry\"><h2 class=\"entry-title\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/your-auckland-optometrists-encourage-you-to-love-what-you-look-through/\" rel=\"bookmark\">Your Auckland Optometrists encourage you to “Love What You Look Through”</a></h2> \n<div class=\"post-info\"><span class=\"date published time\" title=\"2015-02-01T13:08:11+00:00\">01/02/2015</span>  by <span class=\"author vcard\"><span class=\"fn\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/author/admin/\" rel=\"author\">admin</a></span></span> ·  </div><div class=\"entry-content\"><p>We want you to “Love What You Look Through”! As one of Aucklands leading Independent Optometrists &amp; Eyewear Specialists we know how important it is for you to not only see clearly but also feel great. That is why we offer such a wide range of styles and colours!</p>\n<p>With frames starting at $69, Campuspecs believes that fashion doesn’t need to break the bank. Many of the brands stocked here, including Chevrolet, XVO and Modem Girl are new to New Zealand, and the broad range of frames, in diverse colours and materials mean every client has a choice of over 350 options when selecting their new frames.</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/about-us/meet-the-team/\">Lisa and Bernice</a> our Optometrist and Managing Dispensing Optician respectively, would love to see you, they can help you look great and see better, they can help you select frames that will suit your face shape (or if you would like to do some research before coming in to see us take a look at <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/frames-for-faces/\" target=\"_blank\">this article</a>), plus if you would like some inspiration on hot eyewear trends for 2015, check out this <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/hot-eyewear-trends-for-2015/\" target=\"_blank\">article</a>. We’ve introduced the latest eye care technology and frame designs to ensure you look, and see, the best you can. We can also help you with contact lenses, we have a great selection of competitively priced daily and monthly disposables.</p>\n<p><strong>During February and March, if you spend over $400 on new eyewear, we’ll give you $100 off.</strong></p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-1245\" src=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/SliderCampus_Offers_FebMar.jpg\" alt=\"SliderCampus_Offers_FebMar\" width=\"960\" height=\"380\"></p>\n<p>We want you to be able to see our pricing clearly, that’s why we’ve produced your “Eyewear Menu”…</p>\n<hr>\n<h1 style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>YOUR EYEWEAR MENU</strong></h1>\n<hr>\n<h1 style=\"text-align: center;\"></h1>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Frames</strong> — from <strong>$69</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Complete Specs</strong> — from <strong>$200</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em>includes standard single vision, anti-reflective lenses</em></p>\n<hr>\n<h3 style=\"text-align: center;\">OPTIONAL UPGRADES<em><br>\n</em></h3>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Thin Lenses</strong> (1.61) — <strong>$60</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Extra Thin Lenses</strong> (1.67) — <strong>$90</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Super Thin Lenses</strong> (1.74) — <strong>$120</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">♦♦♦</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Bifocal Lenses</strong> — <strong>$120</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Occupational Lenses</strong> — <strong>$140</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Progressive Lenses</strong> — <strong>$220</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">♦♦♦</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Tint &amp; UV</strong> — <strong>$60</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Polarising</strong> — <strong>$120</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Photochromic</strong> — <strong>$160</strong></p>\n<hr>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">\n</p></div><div class=\"post-meta\"><span class=\"categories\">Filed Under: <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-wear/\" rel=\"category tag\">EYE WEAR</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eyewear/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eyewear</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/fashion/\" rel=\"category tag\">Fashion</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/news/\" rel=\"category tag\">News</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/store-updates/\" rel=\"category tag\">Store Updates</a></span> · </div></div><div class=\"post-1240 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-eye-care category-eye-examination category-eye-health category-eyewear category-news category-uncategorized entry\"><h2 class=\"entry-title\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/focussing-on-student-eyecare-in-auckland/\" rel=\"bookmark\">Focussing On Student Eyecare in Auckland</a></h2> \n<div class=\"post-info\"><span class=\"date published time\" title=\"2015-01-28T15:14:19+00:00\">28/01/2015</span>  by <span class=\"author vcard\"><span class=\"fn\"><a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/author/admin/\" rel=\"author\">admin</a></span></span> ·  </div><div class=\"entry-content\"><p><img class=\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-1243\" src=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/Student-300x200.jpg\" alt=\"Student\" width=\"300\" height=\"200\">As your Auckland CBD optometrists, with only just over a month until the start of Semester 1, we’d like to ask you to focus on something really important, and that’s to make sure your eyes are in tip top condition for the year ahead.</p>\n<p>To that end, we’re offering students the chance to take advantage of a free eye exam for the week beginning 26th January, 2015, you can <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/appointment-enquiry/\" target=\"_blank\">book online</a>, to take advantage of this offer.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>We were the first practice in New Zealand with a primary objective of offering eyecare and optical glasses for students, and helping you maximise your ability to learn has always been important to us. As the city’s only optometry practice offering first-rate eye care specifically tailored for tertiary students, we make it easy for you to take advantage of first rate eye care, benefits include extended opening hours and generous student discounts. We’re located just a short walk from both the University of Auckland and Auckland University of Technology. We are also official Eyecare partners with <a href=\"http://www.studentassist.co.nz/\" target=\"_blank\">Studentsafe.</a></p>\n<p>Our practice focuses on affordable fashion eyewear, with frames starting at $69. Many of our designer brands, including Chevrolet, XVO and Modem Girl are new to New Zealand. The broad range of frames, in diverse colours and materials mean you have a choice of over 350 options when selecting your new frames.</p>\n<p>Campuspecs has invested in leading edge technology so you’ll see clearly, we’re the first optometry practice in New Zealand to utilise the NIDEK Optical Path Difference Scanning System.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</div><div class=\"post-meta\"><span class=\"categories\">Filed Under: <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-care/\" rel=\"category tag\">EYE CARE</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-examination/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eye Examination</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eye-health/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eye Health</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/eyewear/\" rel=\"category tag\">Eyewear</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/category/news/\" rel=\"category tag\">News</a>, <a href=\"http://www.campuspecs.co.nz/ca